This project uses historical climate data to support environmental analysis. The dataset used in this implementation comes from the Copernicus Climate Data Store (ERA5).

1. Copernicus Climate Data Store (ERA5)

The primary source used for this project is the ERA5 Reanalysis dataset, which provides global historical climate data.

You can access the dataset here:
https://cds.climate.copernicus.eu/

Steps:

Create a free account on the Copernicus Climate Data Store.

Navigate to the ERA5 dataset.

Select the climate variables needed for your project (temperature, humidity, pressure, etc.).

Define your geographic location parameters and date range.

Export the data in .grib format.

Because this project is designed to be adaptable, you will need to define your own geographic boundaries and time range based on the region you are analyzing.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
2. NOAA Global Forecast System (GRIB2)

If you prefer working with .grib2 files, you can obtain climate data from the NOAA Global Forecast System (GFS).

Download data here:
https://nomads.ncep.noaa.gov/

NOAA provides atmospheric and weather model data commonly used in meteorology and climate analysis.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
3. NASA POWER Climate Data (CSV / JSON)

If .grib formats are not required for your workflow, NASA provides climate datasets in easier-to-process formats such as CSV and JSON.

Access the dataset here:
https://power.larc.nasa.gov

These datasets are commonly used for:

agricultural modeling

environmental research

climate impact analysis
